wi-Fi security is essential in IoT because devices such as ESP32 boards often transmit sensitive information over wireless networks.
One common attack vector is WPA2 vulnerabilities, where attackers exploit weaknesses in older security protocols to intercept or manipulate network traffic.
Another common attack is the Evil Twin Attack, in which an attacker creates a fake Wi-Fi access point with the same name as a trusted network.
If an IoT device connects to this fake network, the attacker can monitor communications or steal sensitive data.

To secure ESP32-based IoT devices, developers should follow several best practices. Using WPA3 instead of WPA2 provides stronger encryption and
better protection against password-guessing attacks. Certificate pinning ensures that the device communicates only with trusted servers by verifying
a known server certificate, reducing the risk of man-in-the-middle attacks. Developers should also use secure communication protocols such as
HTTPS or MQTTS, keep firmware updated, and use strong, unique Wi-Fi passwords.

Hardcoding Wi-Fi credentials directly into the source code is a poor security practice. If the code is uploaded to a public GitHub repository or 
accessed by an unauthorized person, the network credentials become exposed. Attackers can use these credentials to gain unauthorized access to the
Wi-Fi network, compromise IoT devices, or launch further attacks. A better approach is to store credentials in a separate configuration file that
is excluded from version control using a .gitignore file or to securely provision credentials during device setup.
